          </div>
        </div>

      </div>

      <div class="seo-content">
        <h2>Credit Score Requirements and Application Tips</h2>
        <p>Applying for a new credit card usually requires a hard inquiry on your credit report, which temporarily lowers your score. To maximize your chances of approval, follow these tips:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Check your credit score:</strong> Most premium cards require a "Good" or "Excellent" score (670+ FICO). If your score is lower, consider starting with a secured or student card.</li>
          <li><strong>Lower your utilization:</strong> Pay off existing balances before applying. A high utilization ratio signals risk to lenders.</li>
          <li><strong>Wait between applications:</strong> Don't apply for multiple cards on the same day. Space out applications by at least 3-6 months.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-section">
        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-question">What is the best credit card for beginners?</div>
          <div class="faq-answer">For beginners, a no-annual-fee student card or a secured card is best to build credit safely.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-question">How many credit cards should I have?</div>
          <div class="faq-answer">There is no perfect number, but having 2-3 cards for different spending categories (e.g., one for groceries, one for travel) can maximize rewards while keeping your accounts manageable.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-question">Do travel cards have high annual fees?</div>
          <div class="faq-answer">Premium travel cards have high fees but offer extensive perks. However, there are low-fee and no-fee options available.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-question">What is a 0% APR balance transfer card?</div>
          <div class="faq-answer">These cards offer a promotional period where no interest is charged on transferred balances, making them excellent for paying off existing debt.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-question">Does applying for a new credit card hurt my credit score?</div>
          <div class="faq-answer">Yes, a hard inquiry will temporarily lower your score by a few points. However, the new credit limit can lower your utilization ratio, which improves your score in the long run.</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </main>
  </div>
</SiteLayout>
